data.content:
Yes — two better options depending on your needs:

**Simplest: use `[DataRow]` for inline constants**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**If you need computed/non-constant data, use tuples:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Why these are better:**

- **`DataRow`** — no separate property needed, data lives right on the test, compile-time type checking.
- **Tuples** — type-safe (no `object[]` casting), named fields improve readability, and the test runner can still unpack them into method parameters.

Use `DataRow` when all values are compile-time constants. Use `DynamicData` with tuples when you need runtime-computed values or complex objects.
